    <h2>Smoking & Alcohol on Pregnancy</h2>
    <p>
        - Pregnancy lasts 40 weeks (9 months).<br>
        - In the first 20 weeks most differentiation occurs, and 
        after 6 weeks the placenta and umbilical cord form.<br>
        - The blood of the mother and child do not mix. Instead, they 
        run parallel to each other (for diffusion).<br>
        - Oxygen and glucose will diffuse from mother to child.<br>
        - Waste products such as urea and carbon dioxide filter back to the mother to be removed. 
    </p>
    <h3>Drinking whilst pregnant</h3>
    <p>
        - There is never a safe time to drink alcohol whilst pregnant.<br>
        - Alcohol can cause miscarriages, premature births, damage to organs, 
        affect brain development, fetal alcohol syndrome (which results in facial deformities,
        problems with teeth, jaw and hearing, heart/liver problems, 
        and severe learning disabilities).<br>
        - If someone finds out that they are pregnant after drinking alcohol,
        they should stop drinking and get tested.
    </p>
    <h3>Smoking whilst pregnant</h3>
    <p>
        - One of the chemicals inside cigarette smoke is carbon monoxide (CO).<br>
        - CO is a poisonous gas, as it can bind to haemoglobin instead of oxygen, 
        reducing the amount oxygen that can reach cells of the body.<br>
        - Less oxygen is carried in mothers blood, so less oxygen will diffuse through
        the placenta, so the baby will aerobically respire less and less energy will 
        be released for growth.
    </p>
