    <h2>Effects of ionising radiation</h2>
    <p>
        - Ionising radiation is a form of electromagnetic waves.<br>
        - It is produced by the nuclear reactions of radioactive materials.<br>
        - Ionising radiation can be harmful to living organisms.<br>
        - <b>It causes damage to chromosomes, causing DNA to mutate, and is therefore 
        a carcinogen (cancer-causing).</b><br>
        - In high doses, it comes from: 
        <ul>
            <li>the sun - ultraviolet rays</li>
            <li>X-rays (doctors / dentists)</li>
            <li>radioactive material in the air, soil or water</li>
            <li>accidents in nuclear power plants or explosions from nuclear weapons</li>
        </ul>
        - You are always recieving a (small) dose of ionising radiation from your environment. 
        This is called the background radiation.
    </p>
