    <h2>2.2.7 Cancer</h2>
    <p>
        FSL: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BLITE8uA4Tw">GCSE Biology Revision "Cancer"</a>
    </p>
    <p>
        - Cancer is the result of changes in cells that lead to uncontrolled growth and division.<br>
        - It is caused by a mutation in a gene, or a combination of genes, during mitosis.<br>
        - When mitosis is not regulated correctly, the cell divides uncontrollably, causing a tumour.<br>
        - Not all tumours are cancerous. <b>Benign</b> tumours are growths of abnormal cells 
        which are contained in one area, usually within a membrane. They do not invade other parts of
        the body, and are often simply removed.<br>
        - <b>Malignant</b> tumour cells are cancers. They invade neighbouring tissues and spread to 
        different parts of the body in the blood where they form secondary tumours.<br>
        - They are likely to disrupt the organ that they are in, and can spread to other organs, 
        causing many more problems.<br>
        - Malignant tumours spread through two main methods:
        <ul>
            <li>Metastasis - Cells break off from original tumour, travel through blood & grow 
            somewhere else. (Secondary growth)</li>
            <li>Angiogenesis - Development of new blood vessels</li>
        </ul>
        - This is what makes cancer so dangerous.
    </p>
