    <h3>Genetic risk factors that cause cancer</h3>
    <p>
        - There are also genetic risk factors that cause cancer.<br>
        - Faulty mismatch repair (MMR) genes are more likely to develop cancers of the bowel 
        and reproductive systems. MMR genes are responsible for proofing DNA and 
        making sure it is correct.<br>
        - Faulty BRCA genes are more likely to develop breast and ovarian cancer than 
        people with functioning BRCA genes. They produce proteins responsible for 
        repairing DNA damage, and so if they mutate it can cause cancer.
    </p>
    <h3>Treating Cancer</h3>
    <p>
        The primary methods for treating cancer are:
        <ul>
            <li><b>Surgery</b> - Removing the tumour from the body 
                (if it has not spread; is usually only possible if the cancer is caught early).</li>
            <li><b>Radiotherapy</b> - Using radiation to kill cancer cells. Cancer cells are 
            targeted with radiation which prevents mitosis, but can also damage healthy cells
            (although this is getting better).</li>
            <li><b>Chemotherapy</b> - Using drugs to kill cancer cells. The drugs either make 
            the cells self-destruct, or just stop them dividing. There are many different 
            types of chemotherapy. Lots of them also damage healthy cells that are rapidly 
            dividing however new drugs are being developed to target cancer cells specifically.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
